{
  "query": "What are the most beneficial actions for reducing soil erosion in Mediterranean orchards?",
  "relevant_summary": "- Plant or maintain ground cover in orchards or vineyards: Six replicated, randomized, controlled studies from Chile, Italy, Spain, and the USA found less soil erosion with ground cover than with bare or tilled soils, and one Italian study reported the least erosion with permanent cover crops; four replicated studies from Chile and Spain found more water\u2011stable soil aggregates with seeded cover crops than with tilled or bare soils [1367].\n- Grow cover crops or living mulches between rows: Two studies from France and the USA found reduced erosion under cover crops; one controlled study found soil stability was highest under a grass cover [897].\n- Add compost to the soil: Two replicated, controlled studies from Spain found less erosion with added compost, and four replicated, randomized, controlled studies from Spain and Turkey reported greater soil stability with compost additions [1362].\n- Use reduced tillage: One replicated, randomized, controlled study from Egypt found less erosion with fewer tillage passes, though shallower tillage increased erosion; multiple studies in Spain reported mixed effects on aggregation [1371].",
